{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486656"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:40:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:40:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"153"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/153"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.45,0.02,0.37,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"153"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41749"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/153"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"153"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26685"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"130"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42003"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41749"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 35-year-old woman presents with a four week history of intermittent headaches, and periods of extreme anxiety, reporting palpitations and feeling sweaty. She is not on any medications and does not smoke. She drinks four glasses of wine at weekends. On examination, she appears well, and her blood pressure is 176/90 mmHg, her heart rate is 90/min and regular, and she is afebrile, with no other abnormalities of note. Diagnostic investigations reveal elevated urinary metanephrines, and abdominal CT reveals a mass appearing to arise from the left adrenal gland.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydrochlorothiazide","Surgical excision","Advice regarding diet and lifestyle changes","Phenoxybenzamine","Metoprolol"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe history, laboratory and radiological findings all add up to a diagnosis of phaeochromocytoma. These uncommon catecholamine-secreting tumours arise from the adrenal medulla. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe definitive management of this condition is \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical excision\u003C/strong\u003E, but prior to this, her elevated blood pressure needs to be brought under control. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn alpha-adrenergic blocker such as \u003Cstrong\u003Ephenoxybenzamine\u003C/strong\u003E should be administered prior to beta-blockade to avoid refractory hypertension caused by unopposed alpha-adrenergic stimulation. Phenoxybenzamine is a non-competitive alpha blocker, and is preferred over competitive antagonists such as prazosin because the latter can be displaced from the receptor by surges in endogenous catecholamines - such as are observed in phaeochromocytoma patients. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs a beta-blocker \u003Cstrong\u003Emetoprolol \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be avoided in this case to avoid refractory hypertension from unopposed alpha-adrenergic stimulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA diuretic such as \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E is not used in the treatment of phaeochromocytoma, and diet and lifestyle management are not going to treat her underlying condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Alpha-adrenergic blockers are the preferred agents in the initial blood pressure management in pheochromocytoma."],"references":["Neumann HPH, Young WF, Eng C. Pheochromocytoma and Paraganglionoma. N Engl J Med 2019; 381:552-65."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26685"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"153"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26685"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-23T07:39:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-30T21:01:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"153"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41749"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/